children.subject: I did the exact same thing (taking 61A last summer and then 16A+61B in the fall). I definitely found it to be very doable, since 16A is more structured in terms of having weekly problem sets while 61B is project-based with a more variable workload. I personally spent much more time on 61B particularly because of the difficulty of the projects, but 16A tends to be more conceptually-involved in terms of the actual content if you don't have any prior linear algebra or circuit-related experience. Other than that though, I found the balance between the two classes to be pretty nice and would definitely recommend it!
